        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <date>July 8. 1877</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very glad to hear of the subject which you are investigating, as the results will be very interesting. I fear that you will find very little in my paper, which I dispatch by this morning’s post.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Have you ever heard of Douglas Spalding’s experiments of blinding chickens by placing a little bandage over their heads, as soon as they were removed from the egg. The results were extremely interesting and showed how much was done through inheritance. If you have the volumes of “Nature” for the last five years, you would easily find the article by the index.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>My dear Sir | Yours sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p>
<p>P.S.— If you cannot find Spalding’s paper, <hi rend="doubleUnderline">perhaps</hi> I may succeed, but am not at all sure that I can.— There is a curious paper in Nature 1876 by Romanes on a hen bringing up young ferrets.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">In his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11038.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter of 6 July 1877</ref>, Preyer asked for a copy of CD’s paper, <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8641.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">‘Biographical sketch of an infant’</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See Spalding 1872.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4071.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George John Romanes’s</ref> remarks were in a letter in <hi rend="italic">Nature</hi>, 28 October 1875, pp. 553–4.</note>
        </div>        
            
